answers.body_markdown:
In C++ indices of arrays and standard containers start from 0. So it woul be more correctly to say 

&gt; How to keep removing values at **even** places from a vector until
&gt; we&#39;re just left with one?

Here is a demonstrative program that shows how it can be done.

    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    #include &lt;vector&gt;
    #include &lt;iterator&gt;
    #include &lt;algorithm&gt;
    
    int main() 
    {
    	std::vector&lt;int&gt; v = { 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 3, 1 };
    	
    	while ( v.size() &gt; 1 )
    	{
            // comment these two statements in the release version
    		for ( const auto &amp;item : v ) std::cout &lt;&lt; item &lt;&lt; &#39; &#39;;
    		std::cout &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
    
    		std::vector&lt;int&gt;::size_type i = 0;
    		
    		auto even_pos = [&amp;i] ( const auto &amp; ) { return i++ % 2 == 0; };
    		
    		v.erase( std::remove_if( std::begin( v ), std::end( v ), even_pos ),
    		         std::end( v ) );
    	}
    	
    	for ( const auto &amp;item : v ) std::cout &lt;&lt; item &lt;&lt; &#39; &#39;;
    	std::cout &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
    	
    	return 0;
    }

The program output is

    0 1 1 2 3 5 8 3 1 
    1 2 5 3 
    2 3 
    3 

As for your code then this call

    Jvec.erase(remove(Jvec.begin(), Jvec.end(), oddJ[i]), Jvec.end());

erases not only one but all elements equal to `oddJ[i]` from the vector `Jvec`.

So for example if `oddJ[i]` is equal to `3` then two elements at positions `4` and `7` will be deleted from the vector `Jvec`.

Although correct solutions have been already provided, the same result can be achieved with somewhat simpler code:


    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    #include &lt;vector&gt;
    
    using std::cout;
    using std::vector;
     
    int main()
    {
       vector&lt;int&gt; v = { 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 3, 1 };
     
       while (v.size() &gt; 1)
       {
    		for(size_t i = 0; i &lt; v.size(); i++)
    		{
       			v.erase(v.begin() + i);
    		}
    		for (const auto &amp;i : v) cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; &#39; &#39;;
        	cout &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
       }
       return 0;
    }

Actually, there is a quite neat and fast solution to your problem.

Since you&#39;d like to remove the 1st, 3rd, 5th, etc. indices on each step, the arrays are **0-based**, you should actually remove the 0th, 2nd, 4th indices on each step.

Here are some observations, that are helpful when searching the answer:

 - On each step, the array gets halved, meaning that in `O(logN)` steps you will get an array of size `1`. 

 - On the last step, the searched value has index `0`.

 - On each step (but the last one), the searched value has an odd index, so that it&#39;s preserved, until the array size gets `1`.

So, on the last step the index of the searched value is `0`, on the previous step it had index `1`, on the step before that it had index `3` and so on.

We can clearly see that that starting from `0`, the index gets doubled and then `1` is added, so that it gets odd and not deleted. This happens exactly `log n` times.

So, in order to track the index of the number that we should print in the end, we can do:

    int[] values = {0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 3, 1};
    int n = values.length, index = 0;
    while (n &gt; 1) {
      index = 2 * index + 1;
      n /= 2;
    }
    System.out.println(values[index]);

I wrote the code in Java, but you can easily adapt it do your language of choice.

This gives an overall complexity of `O(logN)`, where `N` is the size of the `values` array.

